            <div type="abstract">
                <head>Abstract</head>
                <p>Surface Plasmon Resonance (SPR) biosensor technology has been successfully used
                    for the detection of various analytes such as proteins, drugs, DNA and
                    microorganisms. SPR based immunosensors that coupled with specific
                    antigen-antibody reaction, have become a promising tool for the quantification
                    of bacteria as it offers sensitive, specific, rapid and label-free detection. In
                    this paper, we review the important issues in the development of SPR-based
                    immunoassays for bacteria detection, concentrating on instrumentation, surface
                    functionalization, liquid hadling and surface regeneration. In addition, this
                    review touches on the recent advances in SPR biosensing for sensitivity
                    enhancement.</p>
